You are writing the **Return Modeling** chapter of an institutional IC Memo.

═══ UNIQUE SCOPE OF THIS CHAPTER ═══
This chapter OWNS return decomposition and IRR math.
DO NOT re-describe deal terms (covered in ch06), capital structure (covered in ch07),
or risks (covered in ch11). Every sentence must advance return analysis.
If a point does not directly inform IRR, fee drag, or benchmark positioning — cut it.

{% if deal_structure == "fund_investment" %}
═══ DEAL TYPE: FUND INVESTMENT ═══
This is a fund-of-funds or feeder investment. Return analysis must:
  • Decompose gross-to-net return through the TWO-LAYER fee stack: deal-level fees
    (management fee + carried interest at the target fund) AND Netz-level fees
    (management fee + performance allocation per Netz's offering memorandum).
  • Model the distribution waterfall as defined in the target fund's offering
    memorandum — return of capital → preferred return → GP catch-up → carry.
  • Compute net-to-LP return AFTER both fee layers. Label each layer explicitly.
  • If the target fund has a hurdle rate, compare the deal's projected return
    to both the target fund hurdle AND Netz's own hurdle rate.
  • For PIK or side-pocket structures, model the cash vs. accrual split separately.
{% else %}
═══ DEAL TYPE: DIRECT LOAN ═══
This is a direct lending / credit facility. Return analysis must:
  • Decompose return into: base coupon + spread + OID/upfront fee (annualised)
    + exit fee (annualised) + PIK accrual (if any).
  • If the loan is floating rate, show returns at the current reference rate AND
    at +200bps / −100bps to capture rate sensitivity.
  • Compute net-to-LP return after Netz management and performance fees only
    (no second-layer fund fees unless a fund vehicle wraps this credit).
  • Compare net IRR to Netz's hurdle rate (if stated in the offering memorandum).
{% endif %}

Cover:
  • Base case IRR and multiple (cite quant data from EvidencePack)
  • Fee income (origination, exit) and PIK if present
  • Cash flow timing and duration
  • Sensitivity to rate changes and prepayment
  • Comparison to fund hurdle rate and benchmark positioning

